WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.920
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.860 --> 00:00:10.290
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:12.740 --> 00:00:16.810
SHAWN D. ROCHESTER: It's a
honor to be here with you guys

00:00:16.810 --> 00:00:17.410
this morning.

00:00:19.970 --> 00:00:22.910
I wrote a new book
called "The Black Tax--

00:00:22.910 --> 00:00:26.150
The Cost of Being Black
in America," and it's

00:00:26.150 --> 00:00:29.450
about what is the financial
cost of discrimination

00:00:29.450 --> 00:00:31.700
against black people.

00:00:31.700 --> 00:00:35.270
Often when people are
talking about discrimination,

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:38.210
we're talking about
the morality of it,

00:00:38.210 --> 00:00:41.640
we're talking about the
injustice associated with it,

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:44.630
and I wanted to take a
different look at it.

00:00:44.630 --> 00:00:50.360
I wanted to look at what is
the financial cost, right?

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:52.400
I wanted to look
at what researchers

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:57.170
have said is that cost,
and then over time,

00:00:57.170 --> 00:01:00.740
see if we can aggregate that
to build a picture of actually

00:01:00.740 --> 00:01:02.460
what's happening.

00:01:02.460 --> 00:01:07.240
So the book is broken
into three parts.

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:08.180
It's lot of words.

00:01:08.180 --> 00:01:09.540
You can focus on me.

00:01:09.540 --> 00:01:12.200
It's OK.

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:16.940
The first part is a look at
the costs of discrimination

00:01:16.940 --> 00:01:19.170
across multiple industries.

00:01:19.170 --> 00:01:26.480
The housing, automotive, job
search, high-end careers,

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:31.940
online commerce,
business, financing,

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:35.400
to see what that
picture looks like.

00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:38.550
The second part
of the book, I try

00:01:38.550 --> 00:01:43.200
to answer a pressing
question which is, how is it

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:48.510
that after 400 years, 40-plus
million African Americans own

00:01:48.510 --> 00:01:52.470
just 2% of US wealth?

00:01:52.470 --> 00:02:01.230
Either we are
consistently inept,

00:02:01.230 --> 00:02:05.310
or there is something else
happening in the environment

00:02:05.310 --> 00:02:07.830
that we need to take
a closer look at.

00:02:07.830 --> 00:02:12.120
The third part of the book, we
explore an economic framework

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:18.610
that I call PHD as a framework
that individuals and families,

00:02:18.610 --> 00:02:20.590
corporations, businesses,
so on and so forth,

00:02:20.590 --> 00:02:25.570
can employ if they want to
address two particularly

00:02:25.570 --> 00:02:27.380
pressing issues.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:31.720
The first is we're missing
6 million jobs and 1.4

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:34.700
million businesses with staff.

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:39.550
Not sole proprietors, businesses
with staff across the broader

00:02:39.550 --> 00:02:43.290
black community in America.

00:02:43.290 --> 00:02:47.370
Those two things
combined with $8 trillion

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:51.140
of net worth that
is also missing

00:02:51.140 --> 00:02:54.560
are the single biggest
drivers for almost all

00:02:54.560 --> 00:03:00.480
of the socioeconomic issues and
challenges that we are facing.

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:03.520
So what is the black tax?

00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:09.160
The black tax is the financial
cost placed on black Americans

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:12.240
by people and our
institutions that

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:18.460
have conscious or unconscious
bias against black Americans.

00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:22.900
Conscious or unconscious bias.

00:03:22.900 --> 00:03:26.850
Either they are
aware or unaware.

00:03:26.850 --> 00:03:30.000
This clearly begs
the question, right?

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.390
Are Americans really biased
against black people,

00:03:34.390 --> 00:03:36.640
or do we just feel that way?

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:38.280
So what I wanted to
do was take a look

00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:41.220
at what research has said.

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:45.600
So in 2012, AP, the
Associated Press,

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:49.830
along with Stanford, Michigan,
University of Chicago

00:03:49.830 --> 00:03:53.790
did a study to try to
ascertain how much bias was

00:03:53.790 --> 00:03:55.590
across the greater electorate.

00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:58.040
And they found a
couple of things.

00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:02.790
They found that the portion of
Americans expressing explicit,

00:04:02.790 --> 00:04:07.360
conscious, they are aware of
it, bias or anti-black attitudes

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:10.650
was about 50% of
the population which

00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:13.730
is a significant portion
of the population.

00:04:13.730 --> 00:04:17.149
They also took a look and said,
how much of the population

00:04:17.149 --> 00:04:21.050
has an implicit or
unconscious bias,

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:28.400
and that's closer to 56%,
about 6 in 10 in 2012.

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:33.040
Harvard has been researching
this for a number of years.

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:35.540
Their researchers developed
something called the Implicit

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:40.070
Association Test that they
use to tease out unconscious

00:04:40.070 --> 00:04:42.800
bias in various people
who take the test,

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:47.040
and over three million
people have taken this test.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:51.460
And what they have found
is that 75% of Americans,

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:57.900
so it's almost 8 out of 10,
have an implicit, unconscious

00:04:57.900 --> 00:05:00.915
preference for white
people over black people.

00:05:03.710 --> 00:05:07.400
They also found that this
automatic preference,

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:12.440
as they call it, predicts
discriminatory behavior

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:16.330
even for people who
earnestly believe that they

00:05:16.330 --> 00:05:18.740
don't discriminate at all.

00:05:18.740 --> 00:05:22.530
As a matter of fact, they say
that this is empirical truth.

00:05:25.380 --> 00:05:33.350
So if this is the
case, then we should

00:05:33.350 --> 00:05:37.400
be able to see some evidence
of this kind of showing up

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:40.080
in a marketplace as opposed
to just talk about it

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:41.780
qualitatively.

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:45.220
So back in 2002, the
university researchers

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:46.810
at University of
Chicago did a study

00:05:46.810 --> 00:05:51.070
and they wanted to take a look
at discrimination in the labor

00:05:51.070 --> 00:05:52.910
market.

00:05:52.910 --> 00:05:57.980
And what they did was
they created resumes,

00:05:57.980 --> 00:06:01.640
and they allowed the
resumes to vary in quality,

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:03.170
what they called quality.

00:06:03.170 --> 00:06:09.320
So this was like the prestige
of the school you went to.

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:13.910
The depth of your experience,
the length of your experience,

00:06:13.910 --> 00:06:15.020
right?

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:19.920
And what they did was
they changed the names

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:21.580
on the resumes.

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:25.330
So they would put white-sounding
names on certain resumes

00:06:25.330 --> 00:06:30.460
and they used Brandon and Emily.

00:06:30.460 --> 00:06:34.460
And they would put, same
resume, black-sounding names.

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:37.550
So Jamal, Lekeisha.

00:06:37.550 --> 00:06:38.050
Right?

00:06:38.050 --> 00:06:41.410
And they would send them
out to various employers.

00:06:41.410 --> 00:06:43.285
And they wanted to see
what the response was.

00:06:43.285 --> 00:06:45.670
So one of the first
things that they saw

00:06:45.670 --> 00:06:49.540
was for the name, the
white-sounding names,

00:06:49.540 --> 00:06:54.280
they saw 50% more callbacks
than the same resume,

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:57.840
very same resume, that just
had a black-sounding name.

00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:02.970
So Emily 50% more
callbacks than Lakeisha.

00:07:02.970 --> 00:07:07.974
No difference on her
resume whatsoever.

00:07:07.974 --> 00:07:09.390
The other thing
that they observed

00:07:09.390 --> 00:07:16.920
was as you increase the quality
of the resumes, so the schools

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:19.570
and the depth of experience
and the length of experience,

00:07:19.570 --> 00:07:23.040
so on and so forth, they saw
with the white-sounding names,

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:25.410
the callbacks went up 30%.

00:07:25.410 --> 00:07:27.840
This makes sense, right?

00:07:27.840 --> 00:07:29.520
Stronger candidates,
yeah, I want

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:32.310
to talk to that young lady, I
want to talk to that young man.

00:07:32.310 --> 00:07:34.530
Fantastic.

00:07:34.530 --> 00:07:39.170
Same resume when the
quality was increased

00:07:39.170 --> 00:07:43.250
but had a black name,
no change in callback.

00:07:43.250 --> 00:07:46.030
Zero incremental interest.

00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:49.160
Statistically insignificant.

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:53.239
Same resume, same level
of quality increase,

00:07:53.239 --> 00:07:53.905
different names.

00:07:56.580 --> 00:08:00.410
Well, they also found
was that to overcome

00:08:00.410 --> 00:08:04.920
this effect of the
name, one might need up

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:09.800
to eight years of
additional experience

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:12.468
if you have a
black-sounding name.

00:08:12.468 --> 00:08:17.460
They found that the level of
discrimination was significant,

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:20.006
and it was uniform
across industries

00:08:20.006 --> 00:08:26.910
and across occupations,
even size of the company.

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:33.929
So another study was done by
a nonprofit research firm,

00:08:33.929 --> 00:08:36.239
and they also wanted
to test discrimination

00:08:36.239 --> 00:08:37.030
in the marketplace.

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:40.919
So what they did was they
went and spoke to businesses.

00:08:40.919 --> 00:08:42.710
They actually did a
really smart thing.

00:08:42.710 --> 00:08:44.085
They went and
spoke to businesses

00:08:44.085 --> 00:08:46.590
and they said, listen, what
are the skills that you need?

00:08:46.590 --> 00:08:48.714
Let's just start
with your desires.

00:08:48.714 --> 00:08:50.130
What are the skills
that you need?

00:08:50.130 --> 00:08:51.505
Tell us the skills
that you need.

00:08:51.505 --> 00:08:53.880
Tell us the skills that
you will hire people

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:55.860
if they have these
things, right?

00:08:55.860 --> 00:08:56.664
Smart thing to do.

00:08:56.664 --> 00:08:58.080
Businesses share
that information.

00:08:58.080 --> 00:08:59.517
Here are the skills
that we need.

00:08:59.517 --> 00:09:01.350
So they say, OK, we're
going to put together

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:06.270
a year-long training program to
develop an enhance those skills

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:07.860
within various candidates.

00:09:07.860 --> 00:09:09.450
If the people have these
skills are you interested?

00:09:09.450 --> 00:09:10.410
Yes, we are interested.

00:09:10.410 --> 00:09:11.580
Of course you're interested.

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:12.480
Right?

00:09:12.480 --> 00:09:16.140
So they go through
this yearlong program,

00:09:16.140 --> 00:09:22.830
and what they observed was
for women, for Hispanics,

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:25.320
for foreign-born participants
in the program whose

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:27.900
skills developed over
the course of that year,

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:31.450
their employment
rates all went up.

00:09:31.450 --> 00:09:34.570
For the African Americans in the
program whose skills increased

00:09:34.570 --> 00:09:41.360
over the course of that year, no
change, no takers, no interest.

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:50.070
Now, the level of discrimination
in the marketplace

00:09:50.070 --> 00:09:51.810
is quite significant.

00:09:51.810 --> 00:09:55.920
And it's so significant that
researchers from Arizona State

00:09:55.920 --> 00:10:02.770
University found that if you are
white with a felony conviction,

00:10:02.770 --> 00:10:06.430
you'll get more callbacks
than a black candidate

00:10:06.430 --> 00:10:09.724
with no record at all.

00:10:09.724 --> 00:10:11.490
Right?

00:10:11.490 --> 00:10:13.770
Think about what that implies.

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:20.625
So you could say, look, I
hear you, I kind of get it,

00:10:20.625 --> 00:10:24.090
my best were regular
people, I'm a high achiever.

00:10:24.090 --> 00:10:24.810
Right?

00:10:24.810 --> 00:10:26.880
What I do, is I go to the top.

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:27.900
You know what I mean?

00:10:27.900 --> 00:10:30.670
Doctor, lawyer, engineer,
that's what we do.

00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:32.450
We don't do this kind
of other business.

00:10:32.450 --> 00:10:33.570
Right?

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:35.460
So I hear you.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:36.770
I get it.

00:10:36.770 --> 00:10:40.500
So another research
study was done

00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:42.420
by a firm called
[? Nexten ?] So they

00:10:42.420 --> 00:10:45.060
wanted to get a sense for
discrimination that might

00:10:45.060 --> 00:10:47.170
be in the legal profession.

00:10:47.170 --> 00:10:48.090
Right?

00:10:48.090 --> 00:10:50.320
So here's what they did.

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:54.660
So they develop a memo, right?

00:10:54.660 --> 00:11:00.630
And in the memo they
proceed to insert errors.

00:11:00.630 --> 00:11:06.960
So you can see errors in grammar
and spelling, errors in fact,

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:11.706
and the analysis
of the fact, OK?

00:11:11.706 --> 00:11:15.810
Have you ever presented a memo
to a senior level executive.

00:11:15.810 --> 00:11:19.370
You can't have these things.

00:11:19.370 --> 00:11:22.240
But these are
embedded in the memo.

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:26.080
And then what they do
is they send this memo

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:29.980
off to 60 law firm partners.

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:31.030
Right?

00:11:31.030 --> 00:11:33.390
And they tell one
half of the group

00:11:33.390 --> 00:11:37.850
the memos written by
a lawyer who is black,

00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:39.780
and they tell an
associate who's black.

00:11:39.780 --> 00:11:42.140
And they tell the
other set of partners

00:11:42.140 --> 00:11:46.620
it's written by an
associate who's white.

00:11:46.620 --> 00:11:50.220
They wanted to see what
the response would be.

00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:52.080
So what was the response?

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:55.020
For the partners who
were reviewing the memo

00:11:55.020 --> 00:11:58.170
and thought it was a white
lawyer that wrote it,

00:11:58.170 --> 00:12:03.860
their grade of the memo
was a 4.1 out of 5.

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:07.810
So a 82, like a B,
kind of B minus.

00:12:07.810 --> 00:12:09.474
Right?

00:12:09.474 --> 00:12:10.640
Nothing to write home about.

00:12:10.640 --> 00:12:16.330
But this is a memo that
has errors in facts,

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:22.080
and the analysis of the facts,
and grammar and spelling.

00:12:22.080 --> 00:12:23.280
Right?

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:25.300
That's a pretty high grade.

00:12:25.300 --> 00:12:28.480
Now, for the
partners that thought

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:34.630
the memo was written by a
black lawyer, 3.2 out of 5.

00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:35.920
That's a failing grade.

00:12:35.920 --> 00:12:36.840
That's a 64.

00:12:36.840 --> 00:12:38.610
You do not pass go.

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:42.640
And not only did they
receive that failing grade,

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:48.061
but their projections of this
person being a good lawyer

00:12:48.061 --> 00:12:50.430
was much, much lower.

00:12:50.430 --> 00:12:53.320
Same memo.

00:12:53.320 --> 00:12:54.330
No difference.

00:12:54.330 --> 00:12:57.420
Just told you one, this is
a white person who wrote it,

00:12:57.420 --> 00:12:59.010
this is a black
person who wrote it.

00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:02.350
Very different take on it.

00:13:02.350 --> 00:13:06.340
Now, another
interesting thing was

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:09.640
in terms of why the grammar
and spelling errors.

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:14.190
When they thought that it was
a white lawyer that wrote it,

00:13:14.190 --> 00:13:17.323
they found three out
of the seven errors.

00:13:17.323 --> 00:13:18.710
Right?

00:13:18.710 --> 00:13:21.590
When they thought that it was
a black lawyer that wrote it,

00:13:21.590 --> 00:13:24.740
they found six out
of seven errors.

00:13:24.740 --> 00:13:28.700
Same number of errors, same
exact paper, just who you think

00:13:28.700 --> 00:13:29.580
wrote it.

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:31.850
That's 100% more errors found.

00:13:31.850 --> 00:13:34.490
Same information.

00:13:34.490 --> 00:13:36.550
Nothing different,
nothing changed.

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:46.730
Now, if you're a partner,
and that's your assessment,

00:13:46.730 --> 00:13:49.220
then it might be
difficult for that person

00:13:49.220 --> 00:13:51.020
to get the mentorship
or to get put

00:13:51.020 --> 00:13:52.700
on special assignments
or the things

00:13:52.700 --> 00:13:56.070
that you would need to get
on a track to be a partner.

00:13:56.070 --> 00:13:56.570
Right?

00:13:56.570 --> 00:13:59.030
That could have a significant
and dramatic effect

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:00.446
because you're
saying, listen, I'm

00:14:00.446 --> 00:14:05.220
not sure that this guy is the
one based on what I've seen.

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:08.870
Now, you might still
do OK as an attorney.

00:14:08.870 --> 00:14:10.320
You can go work someplace else.

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:13.440
But you have the skills
and the availability

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:15.180
and the capabilities
to be a partner,

00:14:15.180 --> 00:14:17.700
but you're not going
to get on that track,

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:20.420
or it's very unlikely.

00:14:20.420 --> 00:14:23.480
And the difference in
earnings over a career

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:28.740
could be $11 million off
of interpretation, not

00:14:28.740 --> 00:14:30.870
the actual work.

00:14:30.870 --> 00:14:34.350
Now, if you think about what's
the impact on the family

00:14:34.350 --> 00:14:35.910
of this individual?

00:14:35.910 --> 00:14:37.720
What's the impact
on the community?

00:14:37.720 --> 00:14:39.660
What's the impact on the church?

00:14:39.660 --> 00:14:42.840
What's the impact on a nonprofit
board that they may sit on?

00:14:42.840 --> 00:14:43.800
So on and so forth.

00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:45.510
It reverberates, right?

00:14:48.020 --> 00:14:52.970
Now, a large law firm, it's only
about 3% of lawyers are black.

00:14:52.970 --> 00:14:55.430
Less than 2% of the
partners are black.

00:14:55.430 --> 00:14:57.260
Does this have
anything to do with it?

00:15:00.038 --> 00:15:01.661
Right?

00:15:01.661 --> 00:15:03.410
Well, you can say,
well, yeah, yeah, yeah,

00:15:03.410 --> 00:15:05.720
but I'm going to be a doctor.

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:07.910
So I'm just going to bypass
all that kind of stuff

00:15:07.910 --> 00:15:10.170
because they just
stick to the facts.

00:15:10.170 --> 00:15:13.894
So the British Medical Journal--

00:15:13.894 --> 00:15:15.935
I should have said that
in like a British accent,

00:15:15.935 --> 00:15:20.340
but I'll do that
next time, right--

00:15:20.340 --> 00:15:22.154
they did some research
and what they found

00:15:22.154 --> 00:15:23.320
was some interesting things.

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:28.960
Number one, they found
that black male doctors

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:30.910
make about $65,000
less, on average,

00:15:30.910 --> 00:15:33.850
