and you're talking about this
100% tax business, right?

00:29:15.244 --> 00:29:16.160
You've got to be easy.

00:29:16.160 --> 00:29:16.930
Slow your roll.

00:29:16.930 --> 00:29:18.420
And I'm saying, you know what?

00:29:18.420 --> 00:29:22.510
I'm going to let you
decide if it's a 100% tax,

00:29:22.510 --> 00:29:25.550
so just walk with me
through the process.

00:29:25.550 --> 00:29:30.660
So the crux, the
foundation of this society

00:29:30.660 --> 00:29:35.540
is sharecropping which is
based on a contract, right?

00:29:35.540 --> 00:29:38.900
The way this worked is the large
mega plantations, a lot of them

00:29:38.900 --> 00:29:41.660
were broken into smaller pieces.

00:29:41.660 --> 00:29:45.920
And black families would
settle on those pieces.

00:29:45.920 --> 00:29:49.670
The idea would be they would
work a portion of the land

00:29:49.670 --> 00:29:51.920
to produce cash
crops, and then they

00:29:51.920 --> 00:29:54.620
would share a portion
of the harvest,

00:29:54.620 --> 00:29:57.440
or any portion of
the harvest, right?

00:29:57.440 --> 00:29:58.700
Now, here's the thing.

00:29:58.700 --> 00:30:02.090
The white landowners set
all the terms and conditions

00:30:02.090 --> 00:30:04.490
on the contract.

00:30:04.490 --> 00:30:07.450
Here's what I want
you to remember.

00:30:07.450 --> 00:30:10.440
You don't get crops tomorrow.

00:30:10.440 --> 00:30:11.160
Right?

00:30:11.160 --> 00:30:15.780
It takes a long time to till
land and clear it and do

00:30:15.780 --> 00:30:17.670
all these kinds of
things before you get it.

00:30:17.670 --> 00:30:19.470
These people have nothing.

00:30:19.470 --> 00:30:24.420
At the end of slavery they
have 0.17% of US wealth,

00:30:24.420 --> 00:30:26.280
effectively nothing.

00:30:26.280 --> 00:30:28.710
So the farmer, the
white farmer, has

00:30:28.710 --> 00:30:34.640
to give them shelter and food
and clothes and seed and tool.

00:30:34.640 --> 00:30:36.360
They had to spot
them all of that

00:30:36.360 --> 00:30:40.455
for an entire year on
credit at rates up to 70%.

00:30:44.181 --> 00:30:44.680
Right?

00:30:44.680 --> 00:30:48.310
And some of these contracts,
if you felt ill or sick

00:30:48.310 --> 00:30:51.430
they had the right to outsource
your portion of the labor

00:30:51.430 --> 00:30:55.044
to someone else and
charge you for it.

00:30:55.044 --> 00:30:59.770
Now, I know what you thinking.

00:30:59.770 --> 00:31:03.701
I would not sign that contract.

00:31:03.701 --> 00:31:04.200
Right?

00:31:04.200 --> 00:31:05.280
I hear you.

00:31:05.280 --> 00:31:07.290
Like, I feel you.

00:31:07.290 --> 00:31:07.890
Right?

00:31:07.890 --> 00:31:09.450
So let's say you
do sign a contract.

00:31:09.450 --> 00:31:12.010
There is a law for that.

00:31:12.010 --> 00:31:15.270
These are called vagrancy
laws because you have no land,

00:31:15.270 --> 00:31:18.190
and you don't have a
means of employment.

00:31:18.190 --> 00:31:20.520
And if you cannot prove that
you're gainfully employed,

00:31:20.520 --> 00:31:23.340
if you are idle, and
you are not a landowner,

00:31:23.340 --> 00:31:27.240
you can be charged with a crime
and put in the state or county

00:31:27.240 --> 00:31:28.540
jail.

00:31:28.540 --> 00:31:30.540
And you can say look,
you guys are super smart.

00:31:30.540 --> 00:31:33.184
You say, all right,
that's not going to work,

00:31:33.184 --> 00:31:34.350
here's what I'm going to do.

00:31:34.350 --> 00:31:36.960
I'm going to sign it, but I'm
just not going to do the work,

00:31:36.960 --> 00:31:39.900
I'm going to break
the contract, right?

00:31:39.900 --> 00:31:42.880
And lo and behold,
there is a law for that,

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:45.510
they're called a contract
enforcement laws, which

00:31:45.510 --> 00:31:48.060
means that if you
break those contracts,

00:31:48.060 --> 00:31:49.730
that you'll be charged
with the crime,

00:31:49.730 --> 00:31:53.760
and you'll be placed in
a state or county jail.

00:31:53.760 --> 00:31:55.350
Right?

00:31:55.350 --> 00:31:56.850
But you guys are beyond smart.

00:31:56.850 --> 00:31:57.660
You say I get that.

00:31:57.660 --> 00:31:58.993
But here's what I'm going to do.

00:31:58.993 --> 00:32:01.770
I'm going to jail, and
I'm not doing nothing,

00:32:01.770 --> 00:32:03.510
and they going to
give me three squares.

00:32:03.510 --> 00:32:04.718
And I'm going to be straight.

00:32:04.718 --> 00:32:06.810
They're going to get tired
of that, and I'm out.

00:32:06.810 --> 00:32:08.850
They have something
for that, and it's

00:32:08.850 --> 00:32:11.210
called convict leasing.

00:32:11.210 --> 00:32:11.930
Right?

00:32:11.930 --> 00:32:13.520
Which means that
as a prisoner, they

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:16.730
lease you out again to
the very same farmer

00:32:16.730 --> 00:32:20.470
that you didn't want to work
for or to a private corporation.

00:32:20.470 --> 00:32:22.810
Now here's the thing
with convict leasing

00:32:22.810 --> 00:32:26.920
that's even potentially
much, much worse than slavery

00:32:26.920 --> 00:32:29.020
in this one respect.

00:32:29.020 --> 00:32:32.230
A slave owner actually
has an interest

00:32:32.230 --> 00:32:34.140
in your residual value.

00:32:34.140 --> 00:32:36.910
They would kill you if need be.

00:32:36.910 --> 00:32:39.010
They would beat you into
an inch of your life,

00:32:39.010 --> 00:32:40.570
but they really
would rather you be

00:32:40.570 --> 00:32:43.990
around for the next 20 or
25 years working, right?

00:32:43.990 --> 00:32:46.090
Under this lease agreement
they had no interest

00:32:46.090 --> 00:32:48.100
in your residual value.

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:50.650
I care not about you
15 years from now.

00:32:50.650 --> 00:32:53.360
What I care about you is
six months, eight months,

00:32:53.360 --> 00:32:56.890
18 months, 13 months,
whatever that time is.

00:32:56.890 --> 00:32:58.300
Right?

00:32:58.300 --> 00:33:03.660
The impact of that is
mortality rates up to 50%.

00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:06.280
Mortality rates.

00:33:06.280 --> 00:33:09.120
So you don't sign
the contract, you

00:33:09.120 --> 00:33:11.550
get put in state
and county jail.

00:33:11.550 --> 00:33:13.980
You break the contract, you
get put state and county jail.

00:33:13.980 --> 00:33:15.396
You decide to sit
in the jail, you

00:33:15.396 --> 00:33:17.130
get convict leased
to the same person

00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:18.900
that you want to
do it for, and now

00:33:18.900 --> 00:33:23.130
your life expectancy is now
50% risk of you being dead.

00:33:23.130 --> 00:33:26.100
And you have a family, and
you have wife and children,

00:33:26.100 --> 00:33:28.920
and so on and so forth, right?

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:35.920
Now, that sounds like
100% tax on your labor.

00:33:35.920 --> 00:33:39.520
I set your income, your revenue.

00:33:39.520 --> 00:33:42.280
I set your expense.

00:33:42.280 --> 00:33:45.097
That means I
control your profit.

00:33:45.097 --> 00:33:47.680
And because I don't want you to
go any place else for somebody

00:33:47.680 --> 00:33:49.555
who's generous, I'm
always going to make sure

00:33:49.555 --> 00:33:52.347
that your expenses are
far more than your profit.

00:33:52.347 --> 00:33:53.680
And I'm going to roll that over.

00:33:53.680 --> 00:33:55.820
That's called debt servitude.

00:33:59.260 --> 00:34:03.810
Now convict leasing,
50% death rates.

00:34:03.810 --> 00:34:06.480
By the way, it's very lucrative.

00:34:06.480 --> 00:34:07.590
Very lucrative.

00:34:07.590 --> 00:34:12.110
Because as a small farmer,
you can afford a whole slave,

00:34:12.110 --> 00:34:15.409
but now you get to rent
one for like two years.

00:34:15.409 --> 00:34:15.949
Right?

00:34:15.949 --> 00:34:18.260
Much more affordable.

00:34:18.260 --> 00:34:22.570
The state made so much
money that in 1914

00:34:22.570 --> 00:34:25.480
the state of Alabama,
20% of their revenues

00:34:25.480 --> 00:34:28.267
were from convict leasing alone.

00:34:28.267 --> 00:34:30.183
Right?

00:34:30.183 --> 00:34:34.300
Now, this system
of laws and custom

00:34:34.300 --> 00:34:40.630
lasted for 75 years
during which time

00:34:40.630 --> 00:34:43.850
4,000 black people were lynched.

00:34:43.850 --> 00:34:49.170
That's a public execution
in an extremely brutal way.

00:34:49.170 --> 00:34:50.380
You can run the math on it.

00:34:50.380 --> 00:34:54.429
4,000 is equivalent to one
person executed publicly

00:34:54.429 --> 00:34:56.830
every week for 75 years.

00:34:56.830 --> 00:34:58.301
You going to get the hint.

00:34:58.301 --> 00:34:59.800
Your children going
to get the hint.

00:34:59.800 --> 00:35:01.508
Your neighbors are
going to get the hint.

00:35:01.508 --> 00:35:03.340
Everybody's going
to get the hint.

00:35:03.340 --> 00:35:03.880
Right?

00:35:03.880 --> 00:35:07.680
Nobody has been prosecuted
for any of those.

00:35:07.680 --> 00:35:08.220
Right?

00:35:08.220 --> 00:35:13.260
That is the condition under
which they are surviving.

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:16.650
That is why it's a 100% tax.

00:35:16.650 --> 00:35:20.710
That is why people call
it as slavery, but just

00:35:20.710 --> 00:35:22.850
by another name.

00:35:22.850 --> 00:35:24.660
It was legal.

00:35:24.660 --> 00:35:27.560
So at the value
extracted with 250

00:35:27.560 --> 00:35:30.860
years was approximately
50 trillion.

00:35:30.860 --> 00:35:31.910
Right?

00:35:31.910 --> 00:35:34.820
And this lasted a third
of that whole period,

00:35:34.820 --> 00:35:38.770
and it was a 100% tax
on their labor, that

00:35:38.770 --> 00:35:41.470
could be $15 trillion
dollars extracted

00:35:41.470 --> 00:35:44.450
over that 75-year period.

00:35:44.450 --> 00:35:47.280
If that is the case, then
I want you to ponder this.

00:35:51.160 --> 00:35:54.610
At emancipation they
lost $22 trillion dollars

00:35:54.610 --> 00:35:56.630
when those people were freed.

00:35:56.630 --> 00:35:59.210
And over the next
75 years, they would

00:35:59.210 --> 00:36:02.600
go and claw back
$15 trillion of it

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:06.030
from the descendants
of those people.

00:36:06.030 --> 00:36:11.800
That's an extraordinary tax with
nothing you can do about it.

00:36:15.020 --> 00:36:23.030
Now, I want to talk also
about education, human capital

00:36:23.030 --> 00:36:27.190
development, critical
and important.

00:36:27.190 --> 00:36:32.260
Now, what you will find is
when the land was returned

00:36:32.260 --> 00:36:34.810
to the planters,
as we talked about,

00:36:34.810 --> 00:36:41.950
they needed an abundant,
ready supply of people

00:36:41.950 --> 00:36:43.610
to work the land.

00:36:43.610 --> 00:36:49.100
They made a deal
with white farmers

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:51.380
because they wanted to
expanded public education

00:36:51.380 --> 00:36:52.772
for their children.

00:36:52.772 --> 00:36:55.540
And they said listen,
we will expand it,

00:36:55.540 --> 00:37:00.400
but we will divert the
resources from black students

00:37:00.400 --> 00:37:02.610
towards the white students.

00:37:02.610 --> 00:37:06.180
And separate but equal in
1898 became a perfect vehicle

00:37:06.180 --> 00:37:07.740
to do that.

00:37:07.740 --> 00:37:10.020
What were some of the
ramifications of that?

00:37:10.020 --> 00:37:14.880
Number one, by 1900, you had one
black teacher for every 1,000

00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:18.990
students, 1,000 students.

00:37:18.990 --> 00:37:23.460
By 1917, we had just
64 public high schools

00:37:23.460 --> 00:37:27.840
across the entire South
for black students.

00:37:27.840 --> 00:37:31.800
44% of all the buildings
that were schools

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:35.250
were constructed and
owned by black people.

00:37:35.250 --> 00:37:39.450
And many of the buildings
that were owned by the public

00:37:39.450 --> 00:37:41.220
had been gifted to
them, but were actually

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:44.647
built by black
people so that they

00:37:44.647 --> 00:37:46.980
could get recognized and get
funding associated with it.

00:37:49.850 --> 00:37:51.260
William H. Baldwin,
the President

00:37:51.260 --> 00:37:52.910
of the General Education Board--

00:37:52.910 --> 00:37:55.460
kind of like the Department
of Education back in the day--

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:57.860
stated that the South
needs Negroes educated

00:37:57.860 --> 00:38:01.970
so that they can be directed to
be the best possible laborers.

00:38:01.970 --> 00:38:03.700
With the right
kind of education,

00:38:03.700 --> 00:38:05.930
the Negro will willingly
work menial jobs

00:38:05.930 --> 00:38:08.390
and will open up an
opportunity for Southern whites

00:38:08.390 --> 00:38:11.550
to perform more expert labor.

00:38:11.550 --> 00:38:13.150
So a couple of quick things.

00:38:13.150 --> 00:38:17.080
When we talk about separate but
equal to put this in a context.

00:38:17.080 --> 00:38:22.620
New, York City,
1920, 50 times more

00:38:22.620 --> 00:38:24.360
is spent on children
in New York City,

00:38:24.360 --> 00:38:26.760
97% of whom are
white, than are spent

00:38:26.760 --> 00:38:31.100
on children in South Carolina.

00:38:31.100 --> 00:38:34.880
Migrants who came to
New York, immigrants, so

00:38:34.880 --> 00:38:38.930
are getting an education that is
significantly more well-funded.

00:38:38.930 --> 00:38:42.790
In the South, for every dollar
invested in a black child,

00:38:42.790 --> 00:38:45.790
you've got five to eight
invested in a white child.

00:38:45.790 --> 00:38:49.120
For every white student,
received 50% more years

00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:54.010
of education, and black
teachers often got 25 to 34%

00:38:54.010 --> 00:38:56.050
of what white
teachers were paid.

00:38:56.050 --> 00:38:59.800
Researchers say
that if you had just

00:38:59.800 --> 00:39:03.431
invested the children equally,
kept all the other stuff

00:39:03.431 --> 00:39:03.930
the same.

00:39:03.930 --> 00:39:05.750
Just invest in the
children equally.

00:39:05.750 --> 00:39:07.320
Do what the law says.

00:39:07.320 --> 00:39:09.737
That would have closed
the earnings gap by 50%,

00:39:09.737 --> 00:39:10.820
just that one thing alone.

00:39:10.820 --> 00:39:13.153
Keep all the discrimination,
keep all that kind of stuff

00:39:13.153 --> 00:39:13.781
in place.

00:39:13.781 --> 00:39:14.280
Right?

00:39:14.280 --> 00:39:14.780
By 50%.

00:39:18.070 --> 00:39:20.590
For a generation, that's
over $600 billion.

00:39:20.590 --> 00:39:28.180
For multiple generations,
from 1898 to almost 1955,

00:39:28.180 --> 00:39:33.070
that could be north
of 3 trillion dollars.

00:39:33.070 --> 00:39:35.710
Then a quick thing I want
to talk about, real quick,

00:39:35.710 --> 00:39:38.380
is what happened to
all the black teachers?

00:39:38.380 --> 00:39:40.697
This was always something
that was curious to me.

00:39:40.697 --> 00:39:43.280
At one point, all black students
got taught by black teachers.

00:39:43.280 --> 00:39:46.570
Now, it's very hard to have
to find black teachers.

00:39:46.570 --> 00:39:54.600
So in 1954, right before
segregation became illegal,

00:39:54.600 --> 00:39:58.950
you had a 82,000 black teachers
for two million students.

00:39:58.950 --> 00:40:03.400
They were 50% of the
black professional class.

00:40:03.400 --> 00:40:06.040
Within a decade of Brown
v. Board of Education,

00:40:06.040 --> 00:40:11.070
40,000 of those
teachers were fired

00:40:11.070 --> 00:40:14.460
wiping out 25% of the
black professional class.

00:40:14.460 --> 00:40:16.920
Researchers say that
90% of black principals

00:40:16.920 --> 00:40:20.130
lost their jobs in
11 southern states.

00:40:20.130 --> 00:40:24.630
The number of black students
applying to be teachers

00:40:24.630 --> 00:40:27.970
dropped within 20,
25 years after that.

00:40:27.970 --> 00:40:31.080
And currently, 18% of
the public school system

00:40:31.080 --> 00:40:35.100
are African American, 7%
of the teachers are black.

00:40:35.100 --> 00:40:39.462
Just 2% of those teachers, of
all teachers, are black males.

00:40:39.462 --> 00:40:41.670
Now, if you look at that
from a different perspective

00:40:41.670 --> 00:40:43.294
it means proportionately,
we're missing

00:40:43.294 --> 00:40:47.140
352,000 black teachers,
public school system today,

00:40:47.140 --> 00:40:48.819
proportionally.

00:40:48.819 --> 00:40:50.610
If you looked at what
they would be earning

00:40:50.610 --> 00:40:52.320
on average, average
teacher salary,

00:40:52.320 --> 00:40:55.830
across that number
of people, 350,000,

00:40:55.830 --> 00:40:58.410
you're talking about
$20 billion that

00:40:58.410 --> 00:41:00.570
is not going to those
teachers, that is not

00:41:00.570 --> 00:41:03.510
going to the black
community this year

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:05.880
and last year and
next year, and that's

00:41:05.880 --> 00:41:09.660
been going on for 60 years now.

00:41:09.660 --> 00:41:14.820
What is the impact of
that on those families?

00:41:14.820 --> 00:41:19.059
So we're not going to talk about
discrimination of labor market,

00:41:19.059 --> 00:41:19.850
we don't have time.

00:41:19.850 --> 00:41:21.910
We're not going to talk
about housing discrimination,

00:41:21.910 --> 00:41:22.710
we don't have time.

00:41:22.710 --> 00:41:24.460
We're not going to
talk about the GI bill,

00:41:24.460 --> 00:41:25.300
we don't have time.

00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:27.508
We're not going to talk
about the black tax from 1965

00:41:27.508 --> 00:41:29.010
to the present, we
don't have time.

00:41:29.010 --> 00:41:31.710
It is all, of course,
available in the book.

